fileChanges.details:
The btn-secondary component uses a gradient animation (btn-gradient-sweep-secondary) on hover that animates --btn-gradient-opacity from 0 to 1. In light mode, the button starts with a transparent background (the gradient at opacity 0). The animation is intended to sweep in a neon-green-to-blue gradient, but on the off-white page background the button can appear 'white on white' during or after the animation if the @property animation isn't fully supported or the gradient is not visible enough.

Fix: Add a fallback background for the light-mode Load More button hover. Add a rule:
```css
.archive:not(.dark) .archive-load-more .btn-secondary:hover {
  background-color: var(--color-off-white);
  border-color: var(--color-charcoal);
}
```
This ensures at minimum the button has a visible charcoal border on hover. However, the real fix should ensure the gradient animation works. A more robust approach: add an explicit `background` on hover that provides a visible fallback beneath the gradient:
```css
.archive:not(.dark) .archive-load-more .btn-secondary:hover {
  border-color: var(--color-charcoal);
}
```
Since the standard btn-secondary hover already sets `border-charcoal text-charcoal!` and the animation should provide the gradient fill, the real issue might be the animation being overridden. Check if the `.archive.dark[data-post-type="post"]` hover rule at xl resolution is somehow leaking. The safest fix: ensure the `:is(.btn-primary, .btn-secondary):hover` global rule's `border-charcoal` keeps the button outlined on off-white. If the gradient animation genuinely fails, add a solid fallback:
```css
.archive:not(.dark) .archive-load-more .btn-secondary:hover {
  background: linear-gradient(90deg, var(--color-neon-green) 0%, var(--color-blue) 70%);
  border-color: var(--color-charcoal);
  color: var(--color-charcoal) !important;
}
```
This provides a non-animated gradient fill as a safe fallback that ensures the button is always visible on hover against the off-white background.
